    slug: "khuwabon-ki-tabeerain",
    description: `Khuwabon Ki Tabeerain is a comprehensive Urdu-language book on the Islamic science of dream interpretation, drawing upon authentic hadith narrations and the established scholarship of classical Islamic exegetes to provide readers with a reliable and methodical guide to understanding their dreams. In Islam, dreams hold a significant place as one of the forty-six portions of prophethood, and this book explores that foundational concept in depth, explaining the categories of dreams recognised in Islamic tradition: true dreams (ruya sadiqah) from Allah, dreams from one's own thoughts and experiences (hulm), and dreams from Shaytan. The author systematically addresses each category, teaching readers how to distinguish between them and what constitutes a genuine Islamic approach to dream interpretation. The book provides detailed interpretations of common dream symbols and imagery, drawing upon the well-known works of Imam Ibn Sirin and other classical scholars who specialised in this field. Each symbol is explained with reference to its Quranic or hadith-based context where applicable, ensuring that interpretations remain grounded in authentic Islamic sources rather than superstition or unfounded cultural beliefs. The text also covers the etiquettes and rulings associated with dreams in Islam, including the recommendation to share good dreams with loved ones, the instruction to seek refuge from disturbing dreams, and the prohibition of fabricating dream interpretations. The author includes a dedicated section on the dreams of the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and his companions, which serve as reference points for understanding the principles of Islamic dream interpretation. Additionally, the book addresses contemporary questions that modern readers may have, such as the significance of recurring dreams, the relationship between a person's spiritual state and the nature of their dreams, and whether certain times or conditions make dreams more likely to be true. Written in accessible Urdu, this book serves as a valuable resource for anyone seeking to understand their dreams through the lens of Islamic scholarship, including students of Islamic studies, general readers curious about this fascinating aspect of Islamic knowledge, and individuals who have experienced meaningful dreams and wish to understand them properly.`,
