    slug: "kia-islam-main-daarhi-farz-hai",
    description: `Kia Islam Main Daarhi Farz Hai is a focused and well-researched Islamic book that examines the question of whether growing a beard is obligatory in Islam, presenting the evidence from the primary sources of Islamic law in a balanced and scholarly manner. The book addresses a topic that has generated considerable discussion and debate within Muslim communities, particularly in modern times when cultural norms around facial hair have shifted significantly. The author begins by establishing the foundational Islamic principle that all matters of worship and religious practice must be referred back to the Quran and the authentic Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and then proceeds to present the specific evidence related to the beard. The hadith narrations commanding Muslim men to grow their beards and trim their moustaches are presented with their full chains of narration and authenticity gradings, allowing readers to assess the strength of the evidence for themselves. The book examines the positions of the four major schools of Islamic jurisprudence on this matter, noting that there is a strong consensus among classical scholars regarding the obligation of the beard, even if there are differences regarding its minimum length and the specifics of its maintenance. The author also addresses common counterarguments and objections that are raised in contemporary discussions, including questions about cultural relativity, the distinction between obligatory acts and recommended acts, and the argument that the beard was merely a cultural practice of the Arabs rather than a religious injunction. Each objection is carefully analysed with reference to the relevant Islamic evidences and scholarly responses. The book further discusses the wisdom and benefits behind the Islamic ruling on the beard, including its role as a visible symbol of Muslim identity, its connection to the natural disposition (fitrah) that Islam encourages, and the lessons it teaches about following the Prophet's example in all aspects of life. The tone throughout the book is respectful and scholarly, avoiding harshness while remaining firm in presenting the established Islamic position. This book is beneficial for Muslim men seeking clarity on this issue, for students of Islamic jurisprudence, and for anyone engaged in discussions about Islamic appearance and identity.`,
    metaDescription: "Kia Islam Main Daarhi Farz Hai examines Quranic and hadith evidence on the obligation of the beard with scholarly analysis and fiqh positions."
